  "title": "Are We a Model or a Document?",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0fde3a81647f5587",
      "text": "Our dreams for this technology are pulled in different directions by competing traditions as to what we put into computers and what we expect to happen there. Hypertext straddles this division and is thus able to go either way. But our dreams are most likely aligned with one or the other."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2cdbd311d5080de1",
      "text": "In the early days of Lisp there was a similar division between the east coast way from MIT and the west coast way from PARC. MIT hackers thought of a program as a living thing coaxed this way or that while it ran. The PARC model had the program safely stored in a file and only brought to life when it was briefly run as written."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c8b400678afd1d29",
      "text": "Wiki and agile grew up together with agile leading the way. The brand new personal computers on desktops were largely inert until brought to life by the hazy dreams of potential users interpreted fresh every day through the suddenly social process of programming."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4140ec10b51ffa8b",
      "text": "Wiki enabled these computing pioneers to articulate what happened when their work shifted daily by writing in hypertext that also shifted daily. Wiki was a model for this new way as well as a document of its progress. Hypertext straddled this divide."
